    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1939-11-03T10:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1939-11-03T10:00:00-05:00" n="1092"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1092">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">760d.61/401: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Steinhardt</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1939-11-03T18:00:00+03:00"
                            >November 3, 1939—6 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received November 3—3:30 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>859. My 853, November 2.<note n="72" xml:id="d1092fn72">Not printed.</note> I am
                    informed that the Finnish delegation is going to the Kremlin at 6 o’clock this
                    afternoon. A member of the Finnish Legation has just advised me that while the
                    violent tone of the <hi rend="italic">Pravda</hi> editorial will undoubtedly
                    render the negotiations still more difficult it does not in the opinion of the
                    Finnish delegation basically alter the situation. He added that according to the
                    text of the speech of the Finnish Foreign Minister as received by the Legation
                    the words which he is quoted as saying in the <hi rend="italic">Pravda</hi>
                    editorial in regard to Russian imperialism and the impossibility of Finland’s
                    accepting the Soviet proposals for the rectification of the frontier north of
                    Leningrad are a fabrication put into the Minister’s mouth by <hi rend="italic"
                        >Pravda</hi>.</p>
                <p>In the light of the foregoing, I consider it disturbing that <hi rend="italic"
                        >Pravda</hi> should have had recourse to such fabrication since, while
                    distortion of meaning and even misquotation are customary Soviet tactics, it is
                    rare that remarks capable of disproof are deliberately invented.</p>
                <p>The <hi rend="italic">Izvestiya</hi> which today appeared even later than <hi
                        rend="italic">Pravda</hi> makes no reference to the Soviet-Finnish
                    negotiations.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Steinhardt</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
